<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="354" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,420,589]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,420,445]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished by a sublinear posterior margin of telson (
<figureCitation box="[916,1004,420,445]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1931,1953]" captionTargetBox="[210,1370,197,1907]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[207,1376,193,1911]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Somatic featUres of Xanthotropis media n. comb. A. Head and left antenna, anterior View (right antenna missing). B. CollUm and tergites 2–3, dorsal View. C. Right paranota of rings 2–4, dorsal View; the red arrows denote the anterolateral teeth. D. Rings 17–19 and telson, dorsal View. Scale lines: 1.00 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439776/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
) and elongated, distally expanded and laminate gonopodal acropodite (
<figureCitation box="[513,649,455,480]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1949,1971]" captionTargetBox="[207,1386,185,1934]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[200,1394,180,1936]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Gonopodal featUres of Xanthotropis media n. comb. A. Left gonopod, lateral View. B. The same, medial View. C. The same, dorsal View. D. Right gonopod, dorsal View (modified from GoloVatch et al., 2004). Scale lines: A–C (0.5 mm), D (1000 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1439778/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Figs. 4A–D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="354" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,420,589]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,492,517]" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">Etymology.</emphasis>
Derived from the Greek, 
<emphasis box="[643,730,492,516]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">xanthos</emphasis>
= yellow + 
<emphasis box="[882,946,493,516]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="354">tropis</emphasis>
= keel (feminine), alluding to the yellow paranota.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
